<paragraph blockId="30.[192,1441,1603,1883]" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">
Males of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1780" box="[347,469,1603,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Nascus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="broteas">
<emphasis box="[347,469,1603,1627]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">N. broteas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[537,653,1603,1627]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
(mean FW length = 
<quantity box="[894,998,1603,1627]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.18" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="31.8">31.8 mm</quantity>
[29.9-31.8, n = 6]; see figures in 
<bibRefCitation author="Cock, M. J. &amp; S. Alston-Smith" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" pagination="25 - 35" refId="ref19128" refString="Cock, M. J., and S. Alston-Smith. 1990. The skipper butterflies (Hesperiidae) of Trinidad. Part 6: Pyrgine, genera group D. Living World 1989 / 1990: 25 - 35." type="journal article" year="1990">Cock and Alston-Smith 1990</bibRefCitation>
) exhibit some variation in the width of the dark bands and margin on the ventral hindwing. Most (8 of 9) have five subapical macules, one has only four. The two females seen (FW length = 
<quantity box="[214,320,1699,1723]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.61" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" unit="mm" value="36.1">36.1 mm</quantity>
, n = 1) are superficially very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Plotz" authorityYear="1882" box="[785,882,1699,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Nascus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solon">
<emphasis box="[785,882,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">N. solon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above). Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1222,1320,1699,1723]" captionStart="Figure 117-120" captionStartId="30.[192,276,1157,1179]" captionTargetBox="[195,1440,191,1146]" captionTargetId="figure-251@30.[192,1446,190,1152]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Figure 117-120. Male genitalia of Pseudonascus and Nascus (from BRAZIL: Rondônia). Structures shown are lateral, dorsal, and ventral views of tegumen, uncus, gnathos, and associated structures; lateral internal view of right valva; lateral view of aedeagus and associated structures; and ventral view of transtilla and juxta. 117) P. paulliniae (GTA 2460). 118) N. phocus (GTA 3534). 119) N. broteas (GTA 7211). 120) N. salon salon (GTA 1725)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4532861" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4532861/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">Fig. 119</figureCitation>
) are more or less as illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, W. H." box="[479,642,1731,1755]" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" refId="ref19451" refString="Evans, W. H. 1952. A Catalogue of the American Hesperiidae in the British Museum. Part II (Groups B, C, D), Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History); London. 178 p." type="book" year="1952">Evans (1952)</bibRefCitation>
; those shown by Williams and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bell, E. L." box="[1012,1144,1731,1755]" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" pagination="89 - 96" refId="ref18787" refString="Bell, E. L. 1934. New American Hesperiidae (Lepidoptera, Rhopalocera). Bulletin of the Brooklyn Entomological Society 29: 89 - 96." type="journal article" year="1934">Bell (1934)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cramer" baseAuthorityYear="1780" box="[1183,1367,1731,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Nascus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="broteas">
<emphasis box="[1183,1367,1731,1755]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">Nascus broteas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Plotz" authorityYear="1882" box="[192,291,1763,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Nascus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solon">
<emphasis box="[192,291,1763,1787]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">N. solon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[528,628,1763,1787]" captionStart="Figure 121-124" captionStartId="31.[192,276,1003,1025]" captionTargetBox="[194,1444,200,969]" captionTargetId="figure-256@31.[190,1446,192,977]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="Figure 121-124. Female genitalia (ventral view) of Pseudonascus and Nascus (from BRAZIL: Rondônia, unless otherwise noted). 121) N. salon salon (GTA 7229). 122) N. broteas (GTA 7228). 123) N. phocus, COSTA RICA (GTA 7230). 124) P. paulliniae (GTA 7233)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4532863" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4532863/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="29">Fig. 122</figureCitation>
) have a narrow and quadrate lamella postvaginalis with a deep Vshaped central notch on its caudal edge. The central portion of the lamella antevaginalis is rectangular, has a central U-shaped notch on its caudal edge, overlays nearly the entire ostium bursae, and nearly reaches the caudal edge of the lamella postvaginalis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4532863" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4532863" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4532863/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="30" startId="31.[192,276,1003,1025]" targetBox="[194,1444,200,969]" targetPageId="31">
